      "01 A PORT CITY An equal collaborative design from the University of Cincinnati, this project designs a resilient Industrial Zone for the flood-prone landscape of Coney Island. The primary goal is to maintain full operationality by identifying high-risk zones within the 100-year flood line. The design implements a system of flood walls and a centralized elevated platform situated above the flood level. This ensures that even during peak flooding, movement between buildings remains uninterrupted. By merging protective barriers with elevated circulation, the project provides a practical infrastructure that preserves urban connectivity and industrial safety in high-water conditions.",
      "I - RAISED PLATFORM (UP!) 2 - PUNCTURED PLATFORM (DOWN! Historically, the site's 100-year flood level occurred every decade, making the previous park's maintenance unsustainable. Our design shifts from resisting water to managing its flow. By utilizing natural high points, we implemented an elevated platform system for core functions. The architecture allows floodwaters to enter and exit the site freely, preventing stagnation and ensuring the industrial zone remains functional and easy to maintain post-flood. HIGH INDUSTRY LIGHT INDUSTRY SHI MARINA INDUSTRY ENTRY RIVERFRONT FOR RESIDENCE RIVER FRONT FOR RESIDENCE RESIDENCE ENTRY LOW DENSITY ENTERTAINMENT RIVERFRONT FOR RESIDENCE HIGH DENSITY HOUSING HIGH DENSITY ENTERTAINMENT EXPLODED AXON PORT - PROMENADE PLATFORM BUILDIN S OAD NETWORK HIO R VERBEN",
