      "CAR MUSEUM BLOCK The central building houses the Car Museum, showcasing vehicles ranging from early models to contemporary innovations. The interior design emphasizes open- ness, incorporating double-height volumes and spatial variety that enhance the visitor experience. A defining feature of the museum is a revolving conveyor belt that wraps around the facade, displaying cars in continuous motion. This element abstractly references Detroit's assembly line heritage, particularly the revolution- ary impact of the Ford Model T, while transforming it into a dynamic architectural expression. FIRST FLOOR PLAN LOBBY - NTRYtEXtT---- MOBIUS STIP ART INSTLATION JIK CAR DISPLAY DRAG RACE VIEW STNAMP i v w : LOADING DOCK I ENTRY PERANENT COLLECTIOti1 - LIFT LOBBY PERMANENT COLLEFTION - WING B : cocona: ADMI OFFICES: VINTAGE CAR COLLECTION SERVICE ROOM",
      "2nd FLOOR PLAN 3rd FLOOR PLAN 4th FLOOR PLAN WAY SECTION A-A' SECTION B-B' 0-4 CNC ARO?\u0007.CS r Guuk.)uu -e.o.n.nn.o.n.-q OOCX CROC Building Narrative: The design of the building is centered on crafting an immersive spatial journey that celebrates Detroit's rich automotive heritage. Conceived as more than just a museum, the space becomes an experi- ence that captures the city's enduring relationship with innovation, craftsmanship, and motion. From the welcoming entrance that draws visitors inward to the carefully sequenced exhibition zones, every spatial transition is designed to narrate a story of machines, makers, and the spirit of progress. The plan unfolds through interconnected volumes that encourage exploration and curiosity, with open dou- ble-height galleries showcasing iconic car models. Elevated walkways and ramps allow visitors to ex- perience vehicles from multiple perspectives, much like observing a moving assembly line. Strategic visual corridors connect interior spaces to exterior display courts, creating a continuous dialogue be- tween architecture and landscape. Materiality and spatial rhythm reflect Detroit's industrial identity, using steel, concrete, and glass to ex- press strength and transparency. The circulation embodies the city's motion, guiding visitors through time from the pioneering era of the Model T to today's modern automotive design transforming history into a living architectural experience that captures the rhythm, energy, and pride of Detroit's car-mak- ing legacy.",
      "Exploded Axon Perspective Section Concept Narrative: The design of the Detroit Car Museum is inspired by the city's legacy of motion, innovation, and crafts- manship. The architecture draws from Detroit's identity as the birthplace of the modern automobile, translating the energy of production lines, workshops, and urban streets into spatial experiences. The building's form and circulation reflect a sense of continuous movement - where visitors journey through spaces that unfold like the stages of car-making itself, from creation to celebration. A defining element within this concept is the dynamic conveyor belt that loops around the central ex- hibition zone, symbolizing Detroit's revolutionary assembly line. This moving feature not only displays vehicles in motion but also reinforces the city's spirit of progress and innovation. Open galleries, lay- ered walkways, and framed visual connections allow visitors to experience the displays from multiple levels and perspectives, creating a sense of interaction and flow. Each space, whether an exhibit hall, viewing bridge, or public atrium, contributes to a collective narrative - one that honors Detroit's past while embracing its evolving creative future."
